Anonymous Wed 22 Jun 2022 12:59:27 No.48724201 Report

>>48723696
What the other people said. A character that is created by a group or corporate entity is an easier target than one created by an individual. If you want to lewd a Zootopia character, just do it.

Keep in mind that obscure characters created by an individual may have a much more personal meaning to them. Respect them for that. The type & level of lewding is important. Such as the picrel example for your post, imagine if you went full-on scat fetish with her, or public cumbucket slut. The author could be offended & disgusted, and fans might be also, which will not do your reputation any good. If you think you're going to be creating your own content, of any sort, into the future, remember that you're joining a community. Your respect (or lack thereof) for other authors/artists and their creations will follow you.

If you really like a particular creation, take the time to discover their author. Find their websites/communities where they publish, lurk a bit and read the room with the author & fan community. That will tell you a lot about what you may attempt. It's to your benefit to make a serious attempt to communicate with a content creator and get permission. That may not always be practical, but it won't go over well if a particular author is easily accessible and you never even tried before you took liberties with one of their characters.

Accept "No." for an answer if that's what you get. Most people in this community are reasonably flexible, but what you want to do with the character can make a big difference. Keeping it canon might be very important.

In the end, you can write the story with a character in mind, but change enough details so that the character is your own. Then you eliminate most of the possible bullshit & drama should you step over the line of what an author ... or their fanbase ... feels comfortable with. Keep the future in mind. 3 or 8 years from now is not the same world you are creating in today.

Just be cautious & courteous.

6 years in total. However I took a hiatus that lasted a long loooong time until I picked up the pencil again in late-ish 2020. The big hiatus happened, because I worked myself into a corner and I couldn't improve no matter what I tried. It ate away at my mental health and I ultimately quit it in frustration. Over the years and years I constantly got tempted to try again, but always shied away. Ultimately /hmofa/ was the deciding factor. It reminded me a lot of a long-dead general I used to drawfag for and I took the plunge. Drawing again immediately felt different to last time and the welcome I received here prompted me to keep going. However I was determined to make this one count. i did some self-reflection and looked back at my greatest failures as an artist and began working on expunging them directly. I dedicated myself to learning those elusive "fundamentals" that /ic/ talks about all the time.
If you are a struggling artist I would point you to /dig/ here on /trash/. The hurdles you have to overcome as an artist and the process of drawing itself are aetherial and abstract stuff and unfortunately there's only so much I can relay to you with words. Unfortunately it takes a lot of work and you will have scout out the way ahead by yourself. However talking to other artists and looking at resources, tutorials may clue you in on how to proceed faster or more efficiently. Soon you'll look at my drawing again and you'll say "I used to admire that garbage?"

>>48729063
I think you have to find away to separate your art from a desire to meet expectations. Something that I do and may help you is to draw privately without any intent to ever show anyone else. Just fill a few pages with various stuff where you are only interested in what comes out, without rating it good or bad. Once again, easier said than done, but I feel you are putting yourself under an enormous amount of pressure that only restricts you. Do stuff you never did and never tried just to see if you can do it, if it fails, just don't show anyone. In fact, many artists do tons of daily sketches and in the end of day delete everything.

>>48729278
More good points I failed to mention myself or communicated poorly.
"Grinding" is the key word, it takes a lot of work to get better in this trade.

As I mentioned, find people who know what you want to know and ideally ones that can communicate it better. Another thing that helps is to just watch other artists draw. In real-time. Watching the masters work is how apprentices of the olden days learned their trade. Proko's YT channels has tons of drawing demos from highly skilled artists.
Discovering Glenn Vilppu and working over his courses has done wonders for me, but there are plenty of good artists who got nothing out of it. There are many ways to cut this cake.
